213/canvas/1/8d757a85-2672-4127-a791-66c5ee36353b","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T19:44:24.999Z","creator":"Clara Smith","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Like Jonny Greenwood’s dreamy, swooning piano score, the dissolve transition marks a shift in the film. Reynolds will soon after meet Alma, who will change his life entirely. We don’t see Reynolds park his car; instead, at the other end of the dissolve, he is seen walking to the Hotel Victoria but, more importantly, physically moving into a new phase of his life.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-01213/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:1290.1861313868612,650.8576642335768,197.69343065693442,330.01094890510944"}}}]}]}]}